{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011MgQxheKYfo14z2Ai8Bd1M","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The situation is a negative feedback loop:\n1. Pod 1 is starting up but the liveness probe is triggering early (30s delay = 30 seconds before it starts checking, killing it if it fails for too long)\n2. Pod 1 was killed by liveness probe failure (connection refused) - it hadn't even started yet when the liveness probe kicked in\n\nWait, looking at the events more carefully:\n- Pods 1 and 2 were started 89-96 seconds ago\n- crdb-cluster-1 was killed by liveness probe 22 seconds ago (liveness probe failed - connection refused)\n- Now crdb-cluster-1 is restarting again. The liveness probe configuration has a 30-second initial delay before it starts checking, then fails after 6 consecutive failures spaced 10 seconds apart—so roughly 90 seconds total before the pod gets killed. Since the pod was killed 67 seconds into its lifecycle, it seems the probe is failing before the application has time to fully start up.\n\nLooking at the restart count showing zero even after the kill event suggests that might be from the previous pod instance. The pattern emerging is that pod 0 stays running while pods 1 and 2 get killed by readiness probe failures, then when they restart, pod 1 gets killed again—likely by the liveness probe this time before CockroachDB has fully initialized.\n\nThe real problem seems to be that the readiness endpoint is returning 503 even though the cluster initialized successfully with all three nodes. In CockroachDB, readiness fails when a node hasn't joined the cluster or can't serve SQL due to under-replication. When pods 2 and 3 were killed, it left the cluster in an under-replicated state, and now that they're coming back online, the cluster needs time to stabilize before those nodes can become ready. So the timeline doesn't add up. If the probe starts at T+30s with a 10s period and needs 6 failures to kill the pod, it should take until T+80s. But the events show the pod was killed around T+67s, which is too early. There's something off with either the failure threshold or how the restarts are being counted. The pod's been cycling through restarts, and the liveness probe is failing because CockroachDB isn't even listening on the port yet—connection refused means the process hasn't fully started. The cluster was initialized before with all three nodes, so they should theoretically rejoin with their persistent volumes intact, but something's clearly preventing that from happening. The timing still doesn't quite work out, but the real priority is getting the cluster operational. I should wait for pod 0 to stabilize, then directly test the health endpoints and try running SQL queries to understand what's actually failing and why the readiness probe keeps rejecting the pods.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1078,"cache_read_input_tokens":42972,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1078},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a4f25bfa-c061-44f5-97ce-536a57bdfbc1","uuid":"115bd2f2-ea02-4bbb-a4db-d652f192ebc3","request_id":"req_011CcbiwH7jcNWASy655G36d"}
