{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MVAJVJJYK83kvcLRzvrk1i","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see a key difference! Look at the probe settings for crdb-cluster-1:\n- **Liveness:** `delay=30s timeout=1s period=5s #success=1 #failure=3`\n- **Readiness:** `delay=10s timeout=1s period=5s #success=1 #failure=2`\n\nThese are different from crdb-cluster-0:\n- **Liveness:** `delay=30s timeout=5s period=10s #success=1 #failure=6`\n- **Readiness:** `delay=10s timeout=5s period=5s #success=1 #failure=4`\n\nPod 1 has much more aggressive probes across the board—shorter timeouts, faster periods, and lower failure thresholds. With that 1-second timeout on liveness and only 3 failures allowed before restart, combined with the 30-second initial delay, the first probe fires at T+30s and could trigger a restart pretty quickly if the pod is struggling.\n\nThe real issue is that the liveness probe timeout of 1 second is too tight when CockroachDB's heartbeat response takes 3+ seconds, especially under startup load. Even though `/health` should be a quick check, if the system is under pressure or still initializing, it'll time out and kill the pod before it has a chance to stabilize. 1 will get killed before it's ready. The probe settings on pod 1 are much more aggressive—only allowing 45 seconds total before termination, compared to pod 0's 90-second window. If CockroachDB needs more time to initialize and start listening on port 8080, pod 1 fails the liveness check and gets terminated by Kubernetes. The connection refused errors suggest CockroachDB isn't binding port 8080 quickly enough before the readiness probe fires, or the container is restarting and the process hasn't come up yet when probes hit it. With the aggressive probe timing, a restarting process gets killed before it can fully initialize and start listening. CockroachDB could easily take longer than 40 seconds to start given the resource constraints and I/O pressure from compaction, so I need to find a way to give pod 1 more breathing room. I'm considering using a startup probe to delay when the liveness probe becomes active, though that would require modifying the StatefulSet which risks restarting all pods. I'm realizing the resource constraints on this single-node cluster might be the real bottleneck—with 6Gi total across three pods, CockroachDB on pod 1 could be struggling to start up quickly enough to pass the health checks. The task might be asking me to either adjust the probe settings to be more forgiving or identify what's actually causing the startup delay, though examining the Go source code for the health checker might not be the practical path here. Let me look at the StatefulSet configuration to understand what's actually configured.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3472,"cache_read_input_tokens":56730,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3472},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a4f25bfa-c061-44f5-97ce-536a57bdfbc1","uuid":"42a62213-a981-4b6b-9bc2-bf4309642eb8","request_id":"req_011Ccbjw6fZATU8N7Nna5HuB"}
