{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018QVaBdHnNSHV6gfsCP6A5h","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Found it! The StatefulSet command for crdb-cluster-1 explicitly binds the HTTP address to `127.0.0.1:8080` (localhost only) while all other pods bind to `0.0.0.0:8080`:\n\n```bash\nif [ \"$POD_NAME\" = \"crdb-cluster-1\" ]; then\n  HTTP_ADDR=\"127.0.0.1:8080\";\nelse\n  HTTP_ADDR=\"0.0.0.0:8080\";\nfi; exec /cockroach/cockroach start ... --http-addr=${HTTP_ADDR} ...\n```\n\nThis is the root cause of the health check failures. Pod 1's CockroachDB only listens on the loopback interface, but Kubernetes probes come from outside the container using the pod's actual IP address (10.244.0.48:8080), so the connection gets refused.\n\nThe solution is to reconfigure the HTTP server to listen on all interfaces (0.0.0.0:8080) instead of just loopback. I need to patch the StatefulSet to update the `HTTP_ADDR` environment variable.\n\n```","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3982,"cache_read_input_tokens":60202,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3982},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a4f25bfa-c061-44f5-97ce-536a57bdfbc1","uuid":"675fa295-a3da-4e18-ab4c-9941217899b4","request_id":"req_011CcbjzFxEYHd5ZjCbgQfhK"}
