{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KNbqZ1CEdDyQCSxPsSsEte","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Node 1 (crdb-cluster-0) is also returning 503 and has `heartbeat failed on epoch increment`. This is a more serious issue.\n\n\"heartbeat failed on epoch increment\" means that when node 1 tried to heartbeat, its epoch was incremented by another node (meaning another node declared node 1 as dead), and now node 1 can't write its liveness record because the epoch was bumped.\n\nThis is a classic CockroachDB liveness issue:\n1. Node 1's liveness record expires\n2. Another node bumps the epoch to mark node 1 as dead\n3. Node 1 tries to heartbeat but fails because its epoch no longer matches\n4. The node should eventually detect this mismatch, update its local epoch, and retry\n\nBut the heartbeat times are extremely slow—54 to 56 seconds—which suggests node 1 is stuck under severe resource pressure and can't recover from this liveness cycle.\n\nAll three CockroachDB pods are running on the same Kubernetes control-plane node, requesting 3 CPUs total combined with the control plane's own needs. Pebble compaction is adding IO pressure on top of that. The cluster needs breathing room to stabilize, though it's puzzling that nodes 2 and 3 showed as live earlier and SQL queries still work despite these heartbeat failures. The readiness probe is failing because the node's liveness record in the cluster has expired—even though under-replicated ranges show zero, a node needs an up-to-date liveness heartbeat to be considered available by the `/health?ready=1` endpoint. The heartbeat failures are preventing the liveness record from being refreshed, which is why the 503 persists despite the cluster appearing otherwise healthy. The heartbeat is actually succeeding most of the time, but when node 1 slows down due to resource pressure, another node bumps its epoch, causing the next heartbeat attempt to fail. Node 1 then needs to retry with the new epoch, and eventually it does succeed. The readiness probe failures are a symptom of these liveness issues, but the real question is whether this pattern will stabilize or keep cycling.\n\nLet me check the readiness probe configurations - pod 0 has a much more lenient timeout of 5 seconds with 6 failures allowed, while pod 1 is more aggressive at 1 second timeout with only 3 failures. Since I patched the StatefulSet with a new command, I'd expect a rolling update, but pod 0's age suggests it hasn't been restarted yet, which means it's still using the old probe config.\n\nWith `podManagementPolicy: Parallel` and `updateStrategy: RollingUpdate`, the rolling update should replace pods one at a time starting from the highest ordinal, so pod 0 might not have been updated yet. The old command had conditional logic based on the pod name to set different HTTP ports for different pods.\n\nMy patch simplified this to always use `0.0.0.0:8080` for all pods, which is a different command for every pod and should trigger updates. The rolling update might be stalled because pods 0 and 1 aren't ready yet, preventing the controller from proceeding to update pod 0. I should wait for pod 1 to stabilize and become ready. The HTTP binding issue is resolved now—we're getting 503s instead of connection refused errors—but the liveness probe is still failing because the pod hasn't established proper heartbeating yet. Let me just monitor and give it time to recover.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1371,"cache_read_input_tokens":68998,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1371},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a4f25bfa-c061-44f5-97ce-536a57bdfbc1","uuid":"c740a36c-3947-43ae-897a-bac6276315f8","